{
    "blocks": [
        {
            "id": "intro_init",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "__init__ Constructor",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "So far, we've been adding attributes after creating objects. There's a better way! The `__init__` method automatically sets up objects when they're created."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "`__init__` is called a **constructor** - it constructs (initializes) new objects."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "the_problem",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Without `__init__`, setting up objects is tedious:"
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "class Dog:\n    def bark(self):\n        print(f\"{self.name} says Woof!\")\n\ndog = Dog()\ndog.name = \"Buddy\"\ndog.age = 3\ndog.bark()",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Buddy says Woof!"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You have to remember to set `name` and `age` manually for every dog. Easy to forget!"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "using_init",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Using __init__",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "`__init__` is a special method that runs automatically when you create an object. It sets up the initial attributes."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You can define which attributes each object should have by adding them as parameters to the `__init__` method. This way, when you make a new object, you supply values for those attributes right away."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "class Dog:\n    def __init__(self, name, age):\n        self.name = name\n        self.age = age\n    \n    def bark(self):\n        print(f\"{self.name} says Woof!\")\n\ndog = Dog(\"Buddy\", 3)\ndog.bark()",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Buddy says Woof!"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Now when we create a dog with `Dog(\"Buddy\", 3)`, the `__init__` method automatically sets `name` and `age`. Much cleaner!"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quick_check_init",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "When does the `__init__` method run?"
                },
                {
                    "type": "mcq",
                    "content": "",
                    "properties": {
                        "question": "",
                        "options": [
                            "Automatically when creating a new object",
                            "When you call it manually",
                            "At the end of the program"
                        ],
                        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
                        "correctFeedback": "Correct! __init__ runs automatically when objects are created.",
                        "incorrectFeedback": "__init__ runs automatically during object creation.",
                        "explanation": "__init__ initializes objects with their starting values."
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "init_syntax",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The `__init__` method has two underscores before and after `init`. This makes it a special method Python recognizes."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "class Car:\n    def __init__(self, brand, color):\n        self.brand = brand\n        self.color = color\n\ncar1 = Car(\"Toyota\", \"red\")\ncar2 = Car(\"Honda\", \"blue\")\n\nprint(f\"{car1.brand} - {car1.color}\")\nprint(f\"{car2.brand} - {car2.color}\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Toyota - red\nHonda - blue"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "When we create `car1` and `car2`, the `__init__` method automatically assigns the brand and color to each car."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
